Eyes: normal mixture model for microspectophotometric records

Puglisi - 1744998

05 aprile 2018

Bowmaker et al. (1985) analyze data on the peak sensitivity wavelengths for individual microspectophotometric records on a small set of monkeys eyes. WinBUGs Examples Volume II gives the data for one monkey. Below we can see the histogram of the data with a kernel density estimate suggesting two - components normal mixture, as Bowmaker suggested. The considered type of monkey was found to have two cone pigments with peak sensitivities at approximately 536 and 550.

A tipical Normal Mixture model looks like this: \[X|\underline{\theta} \sim \sum_{i=1}^{C} \omega_{c}N(x|\mu_{c}, \tau_{c})\] Where \(\underline{\theta}= (\underline{\mu}, \underline{\tau}, \underline{\omega})\) and \(\omega_{c}\) are the mixture weights. We consider the parametrization of the normal density with the precision \(\tau_{c}=1/\sigma^2_{c}\). We consider the following set of conjugate priors:

\[ \mu_{c} \overset{\text{iid}}{\sim}N(\mu_{c},\tau_{c}) \\ \tau_{c} \overset{\text{iid}} {\sim} Gamma(a_{c},b_{c}) \\ \underline{\omega} \sim Dirichlet(\underline{\alpha}=(\alpha_{1},...,\alpha_{c}))\]

Moreover, the normal mixture admits a latent variable \(\underline{Z_{i}}=(Z_{i1},...,Z_{ic})\) that represent the mixture component the observation i belongs to. \[\underline{Z_{ic}}|\theta \overset{\text{iid}} {\sim} Multinom(1,\underline{\omega}=(\omega_1,...,\omega_{c}))\] Anyway, before starting, I wanted to make some inference about the number of components. Using more components than two, we improve the likelihood, but of course expose ourselves to the danger of over-fitting. Using boot.comp we can see realizations of the likelihood for testing the null hypothesis of a k-component fit versus the alternative hypothesis of a (k+1)-component fit for normal mixture models. A p-value is calculated for each test, when the p-value goes above the significance level, the testing terminates. This test uses the following test statistics: \[ 2(log(L_{k+1})-log(L_{k})) \sim \chi^2_{dim(k+1)-dim(k)} \] fter the third component this difference goes to zero, so, after the second component, the other components are not significant.

Also we can notice that the p-values for the second component leads to refuse the null hypothesis (H0: 1 component against 2 components), instead the second p-value leads to accept the 2 component model against a three component model.

a$p.values
## [1] 0.02 0.61

Another instrument that I used to check for the number of components is the function GaussianMixture in the package SBic. This creates an object representing a family of mixture models up to a specified maximum number of components (maxNumComponents=15 considered), in particular it gives the BIC for each model considered. BIC attempts to resolve this overfitting problem by introducing a penalty term for the number of parameters in the model. In fact the BIC is defined as: \[ BIC= \ln(n)k-2ln(\hat{L})\]

As we can notice in the results, the more are the parameters, the more the model is penalized. Also the BIC gives the best output for the 2 component model.

Posterior Predictions on my own

I need to sample from the posterior distribution of the parameters. To compute the full conditional distribution of the parameters iteratively, I built the function ParPost, that start from the initial prior setting for \(\mu_{c}, \tau_{c} and \underline{\omega_{c}}\). Thanks to the ParPost function we use the Gibbs sampler to sample from the full conditional distributions of the parameters, conditional on the other parameters of the model. In the l\(th\) iteration of the loop, the function built the full-conditional distribution for each parameter in this way: \[ \underline{\omega}^{(l)}|\underline{z}^{(l-1)} \sim Dirichlet (\alpha_{1}+N_{1}^{(l-1)},\cdots,\alpha_{c}+N_{c}^{(l-1)}) \\ \tau_{c}^{(l)}| \mu_{c}^{(l-1)}, \underline{z}^{(l-1)}, \underline {x} \overset{\text{iid}} {\sim} Gamma(a_{0}+ \frac{N_{c}^{(l-1)}}{2},\ b_{0}+ \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N}z_{ic}^{(l)}(x_{i}-\mu_{c}^{(l-1)})^2}{2}) \\ \mu_{c}^{(l)}| \tau_{c}^{(l)}, \underline{z}^{(l-1)}, \underline{x} \sim N( \ \delta_{c}^{(l)}+\bar{x}_{c}^{(l-1)}+(1-\delta_{c}^{(l)})\mu_{0}, \ \tau_{0}+N_{c}^{(l-1)}\tau_{c}^{(l)} ) \\ \underline{z}_{i}^{(l)}| \underline{\tau}_{c}^{(l)}, \underline{\mu}^{(l)}, \underline{x} \sim Multinom \ (1, p_{i1}^{(l)}, \cdots , p_{ic}^{(l)} ) \] where \(\delta_{c}^{(l)}=\frac{N_{c}^{(l-1)} \tau_{c}^{(l)}}{\tau_{0}+N_{c}^{(l-1)} \tau_{c}^{(l)}}\) and \(p_{ic}^{(l)}=\frac{\omega_{c}^{(l-1)}N(x_{i}|\mu_{c}^{(l)})}{\sum_{c=1}^{C}\omega_{c}^{(l)}N(x_{i}|\mu_{c}^{(l)})}\)

ParPost<- function(y, aDir, bDir, a, b, z, numiter, n0, mu0, tau20){
  EstMat<- matrix(0, numiter, 4)
  
  set.seed(12345)
  for (i in 1:numiter) {
    
    n=c(sum(z==1),sum(z==2))  
    
    EmpMean=c(mean(y[z==1]),mean(y[z==2]))   
    
    sy2 = c(sum((y[z==1]-EmpMean[1])^2),sum((y[z==2]-EmpMean[2])^2))

    # posterior delle dir (pesi delle componenti)
    #era una dir con marginale beta(aDIr, bDir) ---> beta(aDir+Nc, bDir+Nc)
    w = rbeta(1,aDir+n[1],bDir+n[2])
    
    # posterior del precision parameter 
    # era una Gamma(a,b)----> gamma( )
    bgamma= c(b+(sy2[1])/2, b+(sy2[2])/2)
    SigmaPost = mean(rgamma(2,a+(n/2),bgamma))
    
    # posterior di mu
    # era una Norm(mu0, tau20)---> Norm(mc, tauc)
    
    tau_c= 1/(mean(tau20)+(length(y)*SigmaPost))
    delta<-(SigmaPost*length(y))/(mean(tau20)+(SigmaPost*length(y)))
    mu_c= (delta*EmpMean)+((1-delta)*mu0) 
    MuPost = rnorm(2,mu_c,sqrt(tau_c))
   
    # post della multinomiale 
    # era una M(1, w=(w1, w2))---> M(1, pc=(p1, p2))
    pz1=w*dnorm(y,MuPost[1],sqrt(1/SigmaPost[1]))
    pz2=(1-w)*dnorm(y,MuPost[2],sqrt(1/SigmaPost[1]))
    pz=pz1/(pz1+pz2) 
    
    for (j in 1:length(y)) {
      z[j]=sample(1:2,size=1,prob=c(pz[j],1-pz[j]))}
    EstMat[i,]=c(w,MuPost,1/SigmaPost)
  }
  return(EstMat )
}
posteriors<- ParPost(y, aDir=0.5, bDir=0.5, a=0.01,b=0.01, z, numiter=20000, n0=c(1,1), mu0=mu, tau20=tau20)

Each row of the EstMat given as result of the ParPost function, is one realization from the posterior distribution of \(\mu_{c}\) and \(\sigma_{c}^2\) and is from one iteration of the Gibbs sampler. Starting from \(\alpha_{1}=1\) and \(\alpha_{2}=1\) for the prior of the Dirichet, \(a=0.01\) and \(b=0.01\) for the prior of Gamma and the mean of the two groups as prior for \(\mu\), the function gives the following results:

Now, to study the convergence of the results we use the Gelman diagnostics. This evaluates MCMC convergence by analyzing the difference between multiple Markov chains. The convergence is assessed by comparing the estimated between-chains and within-chain variances for each model parameter. Large differences between these variances indicate nonconvergence. The gelman.diag returns the Scale Reduction Factors for each parameter. A factor of 1 means that between chain variance and within chain variance are equal , larger values mean that there is still a notable difference between the computed chains. Let \(\hat{I}^{m}=\frac {1}{T}\sum_{i=1}^{T} h(\theta_i^{(m)})\) and \(\hat{I}_T\) the overall estimator which uses all the \(M *T\) simulations. TThe between and within chain variances are given by: \[ B_T=\frac{1}{M} \sum_{m=1}^M (\hat{I}^{(m)} - \hat{I}_{T})^2 \\ W = \frac{1}{M} \sum_{m=1}^M [\frac{1}{T}\sum_{i=1}^{T}(h(\theta_i^{(m)})-\hat{I}^{(m)}_{T})^2] \] So the Potential Scale Factor (PSRF) is: \[ R_T=\frac {\frac{T-1}{T}W_T+\frac{M+1}{M}B_T}{W_T}\frac{v_T}{v_t-2}\] So if the M chains have converged to the target posterior distribution, then PSRF should be close to 1 and the assumption of homogeneity mean follows. From the results we can say that the chain have converged.

Choosing the model

To compare the models I decided to use the DIC. The Deviance Information Criterion (DIC) is a way of measuring model fit for Bayesian models. It is conceptually similar to AIC and BIC. Like AIC and BIC, lower values of DIC indicate a better model fit. The equation of the DIC is: \[DIC = -2 (L - P)\] Where L is the log-likelihood of the data given the posterior means of the parameters \(\hat{\theta}\) given by \(L=log p(y|\hat{\theta})\). \(\hat{\theta}\) can be obtained by taking the mean of the posterior chains. The other term in the DIC equation is P, which is an estimate of the effective number of parameters in the model and is given by:

\[P = 2 [L - \frac{1}{S} \sum_{s=1}^{S} log~p(y|\theta_s) ]\]

logLikelihood = function(y, theta) {
  #Get the individual parameters out of theta.
  p<- theta[1]
  mu1 = theta[2]
  mu2<- theta[3]
  sigma1= theta[4]
  pred = rep(0,length(y))
  for (i in 1:length(y)){pred[i]=p*dnorm(y[i],mu1,sqrt(sigma1))+(1-p)*dnorm(y[i],mu2,sqrt(sigma1))}
    
 
  return(sum(log(pred)))
}

calculateDIC = function(y, theta_post) {
  #Calculate L
  theta_hat = apply(theta_post, 2, mean)
  L = logLikelihood(y, theta_hat)
  
  #Calculate P
  S = nrow(theta_post) #S = number of iterations
  #Add up the log likelihoods of each iteration
  llSum = 0
  for (s in 1:S) {
    theta_s = theta_post[s,]
    llSum = llSum + logLikelihood(y, theta_s)
  }
  P = 2 * (L - (1 / S * llSum))
  
  #Calculate DIC
  DIC = -2 * (L - P)
  
  list(DIC=DIC, P=P, L=L)
}
em<-calculateDIC(y, posteriors)
